          "gap": 20,
          "padding": [
            20,
            24
          ],
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "Odgd3",
              "name": "Timestamp Badge",
              "width": 56,
              "gap": 4,
              "padding": [
                4,
                0
              ],
              "alignItems": "center",
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "tJ3kS",
                  "name": "Timestamp",
                  "fill": "#0a0a0a",
                  "content": "15:30",
                  "fontFamily": "Geist Mono",
                  "fontSize": 12,
                  "fontWeight": "500"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "id": "FwFsX",
              "name": "Paragraph Text",
              "fill": "#0a0a0a",
              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "content": "The biggest gap I see is treating idempotency as an implementation detail rather than a design constraint. If your handlers aren't idempotent, your retries will corrupt state.",
              "lineHeight": 1.7,
              "fontFamily": "Geist",
              "fontSize": 15,
              "fontWeight": "normal"
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "KseFd",
              "name": "Playing Indicator",
              "width": 8,
              "height": 8,
              "fill": "#0a0a0a",
              "cornerRadius": 4
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "frame",
          "id": "mCGHj",
          "name": "Transcript List/Desktop",
          "reusable": true,
          "width": 720,
          "layout": "vertical",
          "children": [
            {
              "id": "Loa5S",
              "type": "ref",
              "ref": "kFZkz",
              "name": "Transcript Para 00:00",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "descendants": {
                "d5mMK7": {
                  "content": "00:00"
                },
                "xhstH": {
                  "content": "Welcome to Virtually Built. Today we're talking about durability in distributed systems — what it means, why it matters, and how teams get it wrong."
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "X0v7VO",
              "type": "ref",
              "ref": "kFZkz",
              "name": "Transcript Para 02:14",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "descendants": {
                "d5mMK7": {
                  "content": "02:14"
                },
                "xhstH": {
                  "content": "When we say durability, we're not just talking about data surviving a crash. We're talking about the system's ability to remain correct and recoverable when components fail independently."
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "YprxJ",
              "type": "ref",
              "ref": "kFZkz",
              "name": "Transcript Para 08:42",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "descendants": {
                "d5mMK7": {
                  "content": "08:42"
                },
                "xhstH": {
                  "content": "The saga pattern is one approach, but it's not a silver bullet. Sarah, you've shipped sagas at scale — what do teams underestimate?"
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ZNxHK",
              "type": "ref",
              "ref": "syMmF",
              "name": "Transcript Para 15:30",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "descendants": {
                "tJ3kS": {
                  "content": "15:30"
                },
                "FwFsX": {
                  "content": "The biggest gap I see is treating idempotency as an implementation detail rather than a design constraint. If your handlers aren't idempotent, your retries will corrupt state."
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CmVzn",
              "type": "ref",
              "ref": "kFZkz",
              "name": "Transcript Para 22:18",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "descendants": {
                "d5mMK7": {
                  "content": "22:18"
                },
                "xhstH": {
                  "content": "That's a great point about organisational habits. Durability isn't just an architecture diagram — it's how your on-call runbooks, your deploy process, and your testing culture reinforce the same guarantees."
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "h4CKIG",
              "type": "ref",
              "ref": "kFZkz",
              "name": "Transcript Para 31:05",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "descendants": {
                "d5mMK7": {
                  "content": "31:05"
                },
                "xhstH": {
                  "content": "We'll leave links in the show notes for the papers and blog posts we referenced. Thanks for listening — see you in two weeks."
                }
              }
            }
          ]
        },
